<h2>HVAC Systems in New Hampshire</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>New Hampshire's continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, with heating degree days ranging from approximately 6,500 in southern areas to over 8,000 in northern regions, and cooling degree days typically ranging from 400-800 annually. The state experiences significant seasonal temperature variations, with winter lows often reaching -10¬∞F to -20¬∞F and summer highs occasionally exceeding 90¬∞F. This climate demands HVAC systems capable of efficient operation across a wide temperature range.</p>

<p>Heating represents the largest energy expense for most New Hampshire households, accounting for 40-60% of annual energy consumption. Traditional heating methods include oil, natural gas, propane, and electric resistance heating. However, modern heat pump technology has become increasingly viable even in New Hampshire's cold climate, with cold-climate heat pumps now capable of providing efficient heating down to -15¬∞F or lower. These advanced systems can provide 2-3 times more heating energy per unit of electricity consumed compared to traditional electric resistance heating.</p>

<p>Air conditioning needs in New Hampshire vary significantly by region and individual comfort preferences. While central air conditioning wasn't traditionally common due to relatively mild summers, increasing summer temperatures and humidity levels have made cooling systems more desirable. Many homeowners opt for heat pump systems that provide both heating and cooling capabilities, eliminating the need for separate heating and cooling equipment while maximizing energy efficiency year-round.</p>

