<p>Ductless mini-split systems have gained popularity in New Hampshire for their versatility and efficiency. These systems work well for home additions, older homes without existing ductwork, or as supplemental heating and cooling in specific zones. Installation is typically less invasive and expensive than central systems, while still providing excellent efficiency and comfort control.</p>

<h2>New Hampshire Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>New Hampshire homeowners have access to multiple incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar and efficient HVAC installations. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment and installation, and can be carried forward to future tax years if the credit exceeds current year tax liability.</p>

<p>The New Hampshire Public Utilities Commission administers the NHSaves energy efficiency programs, funded by a small charge on all customer electric bills. These programs offer rebates up to \$3,500 for qualified HVAC equipment installations, including heat pumps, high-efficiency furnaces, and central air conditioning systems. Additional rebates are available for insulation, air sealing, and other energy efficiency improvements that complement HVAC and solar installations.</p>

<p>Eversource Energy offers specific rebate programs for customers in their service territory, including rebates for ENERGY STAR certified heat pumps ranging from \$500-1,200 depending on efficiency levels and system type. The utility also provides rebates for high-efficiency water heating equipment and smart thermostats. These utility programs often include promotional periods with enhanced rebate amounts, particularly during off-peak installation seasons.</p>

<p>Property tax exemptions are available for solar installations in New Hampshire, meaning that the added value from solar panels won't increase property tax assessments. Additionally, solar equipment purchases are exempt from the state sales tax, providing immediate savings at the time of purchase. Net metering policies ensure that solar system owners receive full retail credit for excess electricity production, effectively using the electric grid as a battery for solar energy storage.</p>

<p>Financing options include solar loans with terms up to 20 years, often at competitive interest rates that keep monthly payments lower than current electric bills. Some contractors offer Power Purchase Agreements (PPAs) or solar leasing options, though purchasing systems typically provides better long-term financial benefits. PACE financing programs are available in some New Hampshire communities, allowing property owners to finance energy improvements through property tax assessments.</p>

